@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node About "About LibSuck"
LibSuck is a small tool which examines library, device and resource jump-
tables. When there are jumps found which do not jump into ROM like they
use to do, but they jump into RAM (like patches and virusses do) the user
is able to take a better look to the part of the memory where is jumped
to.

This can be done using the in-house LibSuck interactive monitor which is
equipped with interactive disassembling and hex-monitoring. Or by using
an external monitor which is executed by LibSuck.

LibSuck is a piece of code which needs a kickstart V37 or higher and
AmigaGuide.library. Without these things LibSuck will never start...


To get more information about the things found in the tables, LibSuck
uses the @{"dsm.library" LINK dsmlib} created by Dave Jones and the @{"recogpatch.library" LINK patchlib} made by
Marcel de Reuver. LibSuck also uses the developer "FD files" and they
may be crunched: the xfdmaster.library made by Georg Hörmann is used to
decrunch the files.

These first two libraries: dsm and patch  are included in the package,
but may be not the latest versions. LibSuck functions alright without
these libraries but gives a lot more info when they are installed, so
it is more then recommended to use these libs!
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node History "LibSuck back in time"
Below the version history of LibSuck is depicted. Only versions that were
released in public are added to the list. All things added to V1.3 are
mentioned as new for V2.0 since 1.3 was never released on the internet.

@{u}LibSuck V2.1@{uu}
- Patch disassembling using the dsm.library.
- Interactive mode for faster and less space consuming libsucking.
- Read resource jump tables.

@{u}LibSuck V2.0@{uu}
- Implementation of @{"dsm.library" LINK dsmlib} (Dave Jones).
- Implementation of @{"recogpatch.library" LINK patchlib} (Marcel de Reuver).
- Implementation of xfdmaster.library (Georg Hörmann).
- Usage of the developer "Fd files".
- LibSuck-Gui for configuring LibSuck.

@{u}LibSuck V1.2@{uu}
- Internal improvements on jmp-table check.
- improvement on mini-monitor. 

@{u}LibSuck V1.1@{uu}
- LibSuck mini-monitor to reveal non-ROM jumps.

@{u}LibSuck V1.0@{uu}
- Read library jump tables.
- Read device jump tables.
- Make Amiga guide file.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Future "LibSuck travelling forwards in time"
LibSuck is not finished yet. Te be more honest: LibSuck is not finished
at all. Not even for the smallest bit. Euuh. I'm overreacting. Sorry.
This is a list of things I like to include in LibSuck since I did not
have the time to include them yet.

- Snapshot mode. Save all information a virushunter may need in one file.
- Verbose mode. LibSuck tells the user what it is doing during the scan.
- Font selection for the AmigaGuide.
- Sorting the contents of the first page.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Functies "Sucking libs with LibSuck"
LibSuck consists of two executables: LibSuck itself and @{"LibSuck-Gui" LINK Gui} to
configure LibSuck. The only thing you have to do is to start the LibSuck
executable by clicking its icon, or just by starting it via CLI/Shell.

Be patient since LibSuck will examine the system, loading fd files (if
appropriate) and will produce a file. After a while LibSuck will show
the results with a nice AmigaGuide file.

Now the smart part: *:-D
In the AmigaGuide file with the results, every non-ROM jump is a button.
When this button is clicked LibSuck will act as a diassembler. The code
found at the jump will be displayed. Every branch from the mainloop will
be a button again. Pressing this button will open another window with
more disassemble code.
At the bottom of the page there is a button which will reveal the hex-
dump off the patch. The disassembler will show the JMP-table itself 
when the address found is not pointing to an existing RAM address.

When there are fd files installed on the system (and the fd-option is
enabled via LibSuck-Gui) LibSuck will also display the names of the
jumps in the AmigaGuide file. The jmp-instruction itself is disassembled
using the @{"dsm.library" LINK dsmlib} (if present). Sometimes this instruction is patched
to something else, and the dsm.library shows to what it is patched.

When a non-ROM jump is found it may be a known patch. To check for known
patches LibSuck uses the @{"recogpatch.library" LINK patchlib}. This library knows a number of
(harmless) patches.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Gui "The LibSuck Gui"
The LibSuck Gui is designed to adapt the LibSuck configuration
comfortably to your needs. Below the gadgets in the window are shown
with an explainational page:


	@{"  Show header info  " LINK Head_Info }  @{"  External monitor  " LINK Ext_Mon }
	@{"  Hide ROM ptrs     " LINK Hide_ROM }  @{"  Use fd files      " LINK Use_Fd }
	@{"  Hide disk-based   " LINK Hide_Disk }  @{"  Delete tmp file   " LINK Del_Tmp }
	@{"  Multiple pages    " LINK Multi_Page }
	@{"  Interactive       " LINK Interactive }

	@{"  Monitor                                  " LINK Monitor }
	@{"  Fd Files                                 " LINK Fd_Files }
	@{"  Temp Dir                                 " LINK Temp_Dir }

When the right configuration is made the "Save" button can be used to
store the newly made configuration. When the "Use" button is selected
the new configuration will be used until the next reboot. By using
the "Cancel" button the new configuration will be discarded and the
old will remain in place.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Head_Info "Show header info"
Every library/device has a header. In this header information about
the library/device is stored. When this option is checked information
from the lib/dev header is shown at every jump table. When this option
is not checked the information will not be shown.

Header information is shown like this:

Header Information
------------------
Version:	39.2084
Open Count:	1
Negative Size:	828
Positive Size:	3134
ID string:	intuition 39.2084 (2.9.92)

@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Hide_ROM "Hiding the ROM pointers"
When a pointer in the JMP table jumps to a ROM based address it is okay.
This is the way it should be. Ergo: most pointers WILL jump to a ROM
based address. When this option is checked all ROM-Based pointers will be
supressed. Only pointers which are patched will be shown.

When this option is not checked all pointers will be shown, the ones
in ROM and the ones in RAM. Since the ROM pointers are printed also,
the generation of the file will take much longer, and the file will
be much bigger.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Hide_Disk "Hiding the disk-based libs"
When a library is loaded from disk all pointers will jump to RAM. There
is no need (normally) to check these libraries. When this option is
checked no disk-based library will be added to de list. This will de-
crease the file generation time and the size of the file.

When this option is not checked all disk-based libraries that are
loaded in memory will be added to the list.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Multi_Page "Using mutliple pages"
When this option is checked every library/device will get its own
page with the jmp-table information. This is extreme handy when the
file is huge.

When this option is not checked all information is shown on the first
page of the file. This will give a better overview, but only when the
file is small.

Note: The interactive button will be disabled when this option is NOT
checked.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Interactive "Using the interactive mode"
When the interactive option is selected LibSuck will gather its infor-
mation at the moment the user presses a button in the LibSuck guide
window. 

When this option is off LibSuck will start gathering information and
will create a large file. When the file is ready it will open the guide
window displaying the information.
When this option is on, LibSuck will only create a table of contents
and show it in the guide window. When the user selects a library, device
or resource to view, LibSuck will quickly scan that source and open a
window showing only the info about that source.

The benefits of the interactive mode:
- Quick. Information is almost instantanious ready.
- Low memory needed. In the file only info on one source is stored.
- Check changes in the system: Leave the table of contents open. Check
  a source watch the info and close the source window when ready. Load
  a patch. Check the source again and see what has changed which is 
  probably due to the patch.

Note that this interactive mode is not useful when you want to make a
snapshot of your system. If you want to do that you will have to turn
of the interactive mode.

Note: This checkbox will be disabled when the multiple page option
is NOT checked.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Ext_mon "Using an external monitor"
LibSuck is capable of using an external monitor. This monitor will be
used instead of the LibSuck minimonitor. When this option is checked
LibSuck will use the external monitor. When this option is not checked
the LibSuck minimonitor will be used.

The location and arguments of the external monitor can be set with
the @{"Monitor" LINK Monitor } string gadget.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Use_Fd "Using Fd files"
Fd-files are used for developing Amiga software. They describe the
names of the functions inside a library/device. These files are common
with Assemblers and Compilers. Due to copyright stuff they will NOT
be included in the LibSuck package.

But LibSuck can use them! When this option is checked of course. The
path to the Fd files is set using the @{"FD files" LINK Fd_Files } gadget.

When using Fd files a RAM-pointer found will look like:

  -96 (-0x060) DisplayBeep              -> @{"  Jmp $1050004  (1050004)  " SYSTEM ""} IPrefs (39.11)
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Del_Tmp "Deleting the temporary file"
The AmigaGuide file used by LibSuck is called LibSuck.tmp and is stored
in the temporary dir. This dir can be selected via the @{"Temp_Dir" LINK Temp_Dir} gadgets.

When this option is checked the LibSuck.tmp file will be deleted when
LibSucks AmigaGuide window is closed. When this option is not checked
the LibSuck file will not be deleted and can be stored in another
place.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Monitor "Location and arguments of the external monitor"
The location of the ecternal monitor can be entered in two ways. The
hard way is to fill in the path by using the keyboard and the string
gadget. The easy way is to click on the "Fd Files" gadget and using 
the Asl-requester to select the right file.

When the executable is selected the arguments must be entered manualy
in the string gadget (at the right of the name ofcourse). The place
where the memory address must be filled in is marked by "%l" followed
by a "x" for hex notation or followed by a "d" for decimal notation.

Examples:
Dh1:Tools/MyMonitor AhowAddress=%lx
Dh1:Tools/LibSuck Address=%ld
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Fd_Files "The Fd file location"
The location of the fd files can be entered in two ways. The hard way
is to fill in the path by using the keyboard and the string gadget. The
easy way is to click on the "Fd Files" gadget and using the Asl-requester
to select the right dir.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Temp_Dir "The temporary dir"
The location where the temporary files can be stored can be entered
in two ways. The hard way is to fill in the path by using the keyboard
and the string gadget. The easy way is to click on the "Temp Dir" gadget
and using the Asl-requester to select the right dir.
@EndNode

@Rem --------------------------------------------------------------------------

@Node Thanks "Thanks are going to the following people"
Development of large projects such as LibSuck take a lot of time and
effort. Therfore it is nice that there are people outhere helping me
on the LibSuck project with ideas, bug reports and software. This page
in the guide is added to thank the people who helped me. The list is
ordered randomly. (..)


Software
--------
M. de Reuver	- Writer of the @{"recogpatch.library" LINK patchlib} which enabled LibSuck to
		  get the names of the sneaky things found.

D. Jones	- Writer of the @{"dsm.library" LINK dsmlib}. The dsm.library is used to
		  disassemble the code found in the JMP-tables.

G. Hörmann	- Writer of xfdmaster.library. This library is used to
		  decrunch the fd-files (only if they are crunched...).

Ideas
-----
D. Jones and M. de Reuver both helped me with a lot of ideas which made
LibSuck the tool as it is now. Thanks guys!


Ofcourse there are improvements to be made for LibSuck. When you found
a problem, or you have any suggestions, please inform me. Use snail
mail or E-Mail, you can find me @{">here<" LINK Rechten }.
@EndNode

